  {
    "title": "Honestly, reading this, Bangladesh\u2019s Gen Z movement didn\u2019t \u201cfail\u201d because they w...",
    "description": "Honestly, reading this, Bangladesh\u2019s Gen Z movement didn\u2019t \u201cfail\u201d because they weren\u2019t passionate or brave \u2013 they clearly toppled a dictator. Nepal\u2019s youth got smart: they didn\u2019t try to start a brand\u2011new party from scratch. Instead, they joined an existing, well\u2011organized party (the RSP) that already had grassroots reach. They also held elections six months after the protests, while the spirit was still alive. Bangladesh's context got complex \u2014 We waited a year and a half and by then, the momentum had fizzled. Worse, the new National Citizens\u2019 Party (NCP) made alliance with Jamaat\u2011e\u2011Islami \u2013 a conservative, divisive force. That move alienated their own base, especially young women and secular supporters. Meanwhile, the old guard (BNP and Jamaat) just painted themselves as \u201creformers\u201d and soaked up the anti\u2011establishment vote. So it wasn\u2019t about Gen Z being weaker in Bangladesh. It was about organisational naivety, a failed coalition, and letting too much time pass. Nepal\u2019s Gen Z played politics; Bangladesh\u2019s Gen Z stayed protesters a bit too long....",
    "link": "https://www.facebook.com/saerzulkarnain/posts/pfbid0wZ8H1TK46Q87EGVsSBwHQH7d2F9xC8ghe87JNn5oexfxd6tBH2JQ1TxVmnmsTgeFl",
    "guid": "https://www.facebook.com/saerzulkarnain/posts/pfbid0wZ8H1TK46Q87EGVsSBwHQH7d2F9xC8ghe87JNn5oexfxd6tBH2JQ1TxVmnmsTgeFl",
    "pubDate": "2026-04-06T02:12:05.972332+00:00",
